sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K416008
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: When working correctly this reporter construct transcribes Aga2-eCFP from the Gal promoter. If the yeast strain is also expressing Aga1, then this fusion should be anchored onto the plasma membrane, allowing you to visualize eCFP as a halo around the yeast cell.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Russell Durrett
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part comes from a mixture of biobricks that were received in the 2010 initial distribution and from parts that NYU iGEM 2010 made ourselves.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We considered fusing this reporter to a variety of promoters, but in the end chose pGAL because it gives a very high level of transcription and we could turn the reporter on and off

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K416005
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This composite part is the Gal promoter fused to a Ribosome Binding Sequence (or Kozak sequence). It should be used in yeast when the part immediately downstream should be translated. For more information see the pGAL part info - part ID: J63006
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Russell Durrett
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part comes from the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisea and should be used therein.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We designed this part in order to be able to incorporate constructs that we would like to see translated without having to insert an RBS each time. We believe that this promoter sequence fused to the RBS will be useful for future researchers working in Saccharomyces.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K165002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The kozak sequence acts as a eukaryotic RBS. It is cloned directly between a promoter and coding region.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: John Szymanski

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K416000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Aga2 CDS Responsible for Yeast Surface Display
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
The Aga2 protein is fused in frame with a protein that the user wants to display on the yeast cellular surface. Yeast cells constitutively expressing Aga1 (strain EBY100) secrete the Aga2 fusion protein, which associates with Aga1 through two disulfide bonds and quaternary structure to anchor Aga2 to the surface. The fused protein then is displayed on the surface of the yeast cell.
The STOP codon at the end of the CDS was removed to allow for N- and C-terminus fusions.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Russell Durrett
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This parts was biobricked from the pCTCON2 plasmid which was sent to us by Dr. D. K. Wittrup at MIT.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We removed the STOP codon to allow for N- and C-terminal fusions, which have both been proven to occur efficiently.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K416001
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is a 15 amino acid flexible peptide linker protein domain that is useful for creating functional fusion proteins. The linker is to be fused in frame in between two protein domains, separating the two domains so that they each retain original functions yet will be physically connected.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Harris Kaplan
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The DNA came from K.D. Wittrup's lab at MIT, on the pCTCON plasmid used for yeast scFv surface display.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This sequence is meant to be translated between two different protein domains, so no start or stop codon is present.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: ECFP
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: ECFP, yeast optimized for fusion proteins
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Our BioBrick is cyan fluorescent protein which can be used to label proteins in yeast. Therefor it has specific characteristics of BioBrick part for fusion proteins (see design details).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Katja Karstens
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: We changed the format of the ECFP coding part of [[Part:BBa_E2020|BBa_E2020]] into Phillips/Silver standard.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
To enable the fusion with other domains in frame the vector of this BioBrick has no base pair in between the restriction side and the BioBrick. Furthermore, this coding sequence does not include a start codon.
For more information about this issus, see:
Phillips, I.E. and Silver, P.A. "A new Biobrick Assembly Strategy Designed for Facile Protein Engineering."
DSpace http://hdl.handle.net/1721.1/32535 (2006).
